[ a                      owl:Axiom ;
  rdfs:comment           "ES: RNAi-mediated knockdown of RIC-19 by bacterial feeding in unc-108\nmutants did not enhance the movement defects (Fig. 9 A) nor the loss of NLP-21–YFP fluorescence in the DNC axons (Fig. 9, C and D). The RIC-19 RNAi was clearly functional because we could reproduce the loss of NLP-21–YFP fluorescence in wild-type animals by RIC-19 RNAi (Fig. 9, C and D) and also the down-regulation of endogenous RIC-19, as shown by Western blotting (Fig. 9 E). This highly suggests that RAB-2 affects DCV maturation via RIC-19." , "ES: To determine whether RIC-19 is a direct effector of RAB-2, we coexpressed RIC-19 with either wild-type or GTP-restricted (DA) or GDP-bound constitutively inactive (DN) HA-tagged RAB-2 forms in HeLa cells and immunoprecipitated RAB-2 using anti-HA antibodies. RIC-19 could be specifically affinity purified with RAB-2(Q65L)DA and to a lesser extent with wild-type RAB-2 (Fig. 10A) but not with the inactive form RAB-2(S20N)DN, suggesting that RIC-19 is indeed an effector of RAB-2." , "Automated change 2023-03-16: RO:0002406 replaced by RO:0002629" ;
  lego:evidence          :5716c41300000683 , :5716c41300000688 ;
  dc:contributor         "https://orcid.org/0000-0002-1706-4196" ;
  dc:date                "2023-03-16" ;
  owl:annotatedProperty  obo:RO_0002629 ;
  owl:annotatedSource    :5716c41300000677 ;
  owl:annotatedTarget    :5716c41300000671
] .

